  "story": [
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "c933cafaf126019c",
      "text": "## Deficiencies in the Knowledge Base, Failures of the Theorem Prover, Lack of “Fail-Softness”"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "b72d3b04a6907029",
      "text": "The fate of each query from the system is also severely dependent on what rules are present in or absent from the [[knowledge base]]. For instance, had the knowledge “a timepiece is capable of telling time” or “a clock is a timepiece” been missing from Cyc’s base KB, the discovery in the clock example would have failed. Similarly, the case of the theorem prover automatically converting a date format from Unix epoch to clock seconds would not have worked if relevant date conversion knowledge wasn’t present in the KB. More generally, the fate of every decision is put in the hands of a very complex ontology and theorem proving machinery. This is a major concern since we are proposing to utilize this common sense reasoning machinery as a black-box system."
    }
